04212nam a22006735i 9780813548319DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135483197 a10.36019/97808135483192doi  a(DE-B1597)529936  a(OCoLC)593317605  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a363.9/72221 aKluchin, Rebecca M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFit to Be Tied :bSterilization and Reproductive Rights in America, 1950-1980 /cRebecca M. Kluchin. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2009] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b1  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Health and Medicine00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. From Eugenics to Neo-eugenics -- tChapter 2. “Fit” Women and Reproductive Choice -- tChapter 3. Sterilizing “Unfit” Women -- tChapter 4. “Fit” Women Fight Back -- tChapter 5. “Unfit” Women Fight Too -- tChapter 6. Irreconcilable Conflicts -- tChapter 7. The Endurance of Neo-eugenics -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1960s revolutionized American contraceptive practice. Diaphragms, jellies, and condoms with high failure rates gave way to newer choices of the Pill, IUD, and sterilization. Fit to Be Tied provides a history of sterilization and what would prove to become, at once, socially divisive and a popular form of birth control. During the first half of the twentieth century, sterilization (tubal ligation and vasectomy) was a tool of eugenics. Individuals who endorsed crude notions of biological determinism sought to control the reproductive decisions of women they considered "unfit" by nature of race or class, and used surgery to do so. Incorporating first-person narratives, court cases, and official records, Rebecca M. Kluchin examines the evolution of forced sterilization of poor women, especially women of color, in the second half of the century and contrasts it with demands for contraceptive sterilization made by white women and men. She chronicles public acceptance during an era of reproductive and sexual freedom, and the subsequent replacement of the eugenics movement with "neo-eugenic" standards that continued to influence American medical practice, family planning, public policy, and popular sentiment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBirth controlxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aReproductive rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSterilization (Birth control)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354831940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813548319423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813548319.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK